# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engine-configuration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engine-configuration/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:engine-configuration/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:engine-configuration/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:engine-configuration/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:engine-configuration/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:engine-configuration/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:engine-configuration/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:engine-configuration/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:engine-configuration/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:engine-configuration/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:engine-configuration/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] An **axial engine** (sometimes known as a **barrel engine** or **Z-crank engine**) is a type of reciprocating engine with pistons arranged around an output shaft with their axes parallel to the shaft.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Barrel refers to the cylindrical shape of the cylinder group (result of the pistons being spaced evenly around the central crankshaft and aligned parallel to the crankshaft axis) whilst the Z-crank alludes to the shape of the crankshaft.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] As a cam engine, an axial engine can use either a swashplate or a wobble plate to translate the piston motion to rotation.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] A wobble plate is similar to a swashplate, in that the pistons press down on the plate in sequence, imparting a lateral moment that is translated into rotary motion.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] This motion can be simulated by placing a compact disc on a ball bearing at its centre and pressing down at progressive places around its circumference.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The difference is that while a wobble plate nutates, a swash-plate rotates.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] An alternative design, the Rand cam engine, replaces the plate with one or more sinusoidal cam surfaces.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Vanes mounted parallel to a shaft mounted inside a cylindrical 'barrel' that are free to slide up and down ride the sinuous cam, the segments formed by rotor, stator walls and vanes constituting combustion chambers.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In effect these spaces serving the same purpose as the cylinders of an axial engine, and the sinuous cam surface acts as the face of the pistons.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In other respect this form follows the normal cycles of internal combustion but with burning gas directly imparting a force on the cam surface, translated into a rotational force by timing one or more detonations.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] This design eliminates the multiple reciprocal pistons, ball joints and swash plate of a conventional 'barrel' engine but crucially depends on effective sealing provided by sliding and rotating surfaces.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The key advantage of the axial design is that the cylinders are arranged in parallel around the output/crank shaft in contrast to radial and inline engines, both types having cylinders at right angles to the shaft.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] As a result, it is a very compact, cylindrical engine, allowing variation in compression ratio of the engine while running.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In a swashplate engine the piston rods stay parallel with the shaft, and piston side-forces that cause excessive wear can be eliminated almost completely.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The small-end bearing of a traditional connecting rod, one of the most problematic bearings in a traditional engine, is eliminated.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] While axial engines are challenging to make practicable at typical engine operating speeds some cam engines have been tested that offer extremely compact size (approximating to a six-inch (150mm) cube) yet producing approximately forty horsepower at c 7000 rpm, useful for light aerial applications.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The attraction of lightweight and mechanically simple (far fewer major moving parts, in the form of a rotor plus twelve axial vanes forming twenty-four combustion chambers) engines, even with a finite working life, have obvious application for small unmanned aircraft.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 1911 the Macomber Rotary Engine Company of Los Angeles marketed one of the first axial internal-combustion engines, manufactured by the Avis Engine Company of Allston, Massachusetts.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] A four-stroke, air-cooled unit, it had seven cylinders and a variable compression ratio, altered by changing the wobble-plate angle and hence the length of piston stroke.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was called a "rotary engine", because the entire engine rotated apart from the end casings.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Ignition was supplied by a Bosch magneto directly driven from the cam gears.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The high voltage current was then taken to a fixed electrode on the front bearing case, from which the sparks would jump to the spark plugs in the cylinder heads as they passed within 1⁄16 inch (1.6 mm) from it.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] According to Macomber's literature, it was "guaranteed not to overheat".
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The engine was claimed to be able to run at 150 to 1,500 rpm.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] At the normal speed of 1,000 rpm, it reportedly developed 50 hp.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It weighed 230 pounds (100 kg) and it was 28 inches (710 mm) long by 19 inches (480 mm) in diameter.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Pioneer aviator Charles Francis Walsh flew an aircraft powered by a Macomber engine in May 1911, the "Walsh Silver Dart".
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 1913 Statax-Motor of Zürich, Switzerland introduced a swashplate engine design.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Only a single prototype was produced, which is currently held in the Science Museum, London.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 1914 the company moved to London to become the Statax Engine Company and planned on introducing a series of rotary engines; a 3-cylinder of 10 hp, a 5-cylinder of 40 hp, a 7-cylinder of 80 hp, and a 10-cylinder of 100 hp.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It appears only the 40 hp design was ever produced, which was installed in a Caudron G.II for the British 1914 Aerial Derby but was withdrawn before the flight.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Hansen introduced an all-aluminum version of this design in 1922, but it is not clear if they produced it in any quantity.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Much improved versions were introduced by Statax's German division in 1929, producing 42 hp in a new sleeve valve version known as the *29B*.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Greenwood and Raymond of San Francisco acquired the patent rights for the US, Canada, and Japan, and planned a 5-cylinder of 100 hp and a 9-cylinder of 350 hp.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 1917 Anthony Michell obtained patents for his swashplate engine design.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Its unique feature was the means of transferring the load from the pistons to the swashplate, achieved using tilting slipper pads sliding on a film of oil, similar to an axial piston pump.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Another innovation by Michell was his mathematical analysis of the mechanical design, including the mass and motion of the components, so that his engines were in perfect dynamic balance at all speeds.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 1920 Michell established the Crankless Engines Company in Fitzroy (Australia), and produced working prototypes of pumps, compressors, car engines and aero engines, all based on the same basic design.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Engine designer Phil Irving worked for the Crankless Engine Company before his time at HRD.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] A number of companies obtained a manufacturing license for Michell's design.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The most successful of these was the British company Waller and Son, who produced gas boosters.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The largest Michell crankless engine was the XB-4070, a diesel aircraft engine built for the United States Navy.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Consisting of 18 pistons, it was rated at 2000 horsepower and weighed 2150 pounds.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Experimental barrel engines for aircraft use were built and tested by American John O.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Almen of Seattle, Washington in the early 1920s, and by the mid-1920s the water-cooled *Almen A-4* (18 cylinders, two groups of nine each horizontally-opposed) had passed its United States Army Air Corps acceptance tests.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] However, it never entered production, reportedly due to limited funds and the Air Corps' growing emphasis on air-cooled radial engines.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The A-4 had much smaller frontal area than water-cooled engines of comparable power output, and thereby offered better streamlining possibilities.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was rated at 425 hp (317 kW), and weighed only 749 pounds (340 kg), thus giving a power/weight ratio of better than 1:2, a considerable design achievement at the time.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Heraclio Alfaro Fournier was a Spanish aviator who was knighted at the age of 18 by King Alfonso XIII of Spain for designing, building, and flying Spain's first airplane.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] He developed a barrel engine for aircraft use which was later produced by the Indian Motocycle Manufacturing Company as the *Alfaro*.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was a perfect example of the "put in everything" design, as it included a sleeve valve system based on a rotating cylinder head, a design that never entered production on any engine.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was later developed further for use in the Doman helicopter by Stephen duPont, son of the president of the Indian Motorcycle Company, who had been one of Alfaro's students at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The Bristol Axial Engine of the mid-1930s was designed by Charles Benjamin Redrup for the Bristol Tramways and Carriage Company; it was a 7-litre, 9-cylinder, wobble-plate type engine.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was originally conceived as a power unit for buses, possibly because its compact format would allow it to be installed beneath the vehicle's floor.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The engine had a single rotary valve to control induction and exhaust.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Several variants were used in Bristol buses during the late 1930s, the engine going through several versions from RR1 to RR4, which had a power output of 145 hp at 2900 rpm.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Development was halted in 1936 following a change of management at the Bristol company.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Perhaps the most refined of the designs was the British Wooler wobble-plate engine of 1947.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] This 6-cylinder engine was designed by John Wooler, better known as a motorcycle engine designer, for aircraft use.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was similar to the Bristol axial engine but had two wobble-plates, driven by 12 opposed pistons in 6 cylinders.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The engine is often incorrectly referred to as a swashplate engine.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] A single example is preserved in the Aeroplane Gallery of the Science Museum, London.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Some small barrel engines were produced by the H.L.F.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Trebert Engine Works of Rochester, New York for marine usage.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The Dyna-Cam engine originally came from a design by the Blazer brothers, two American engineers in the brass era automotive industry who worked for Studebaker in 1916.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] They sold the rights to Karl Herrmann, Studebaker's head of engineering, who developed the concept over many years, eventually taking out US patent 2237989 in 1941.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It has 6 double-ended pistons working in 6 cylinders, and its 12 combustion chambers are fired every revolution of the drive shaft.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The pistons drive a sine-shaped cam, as opposed to a swashplate or wobble-plate, hence its name.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 1961, at the age of 80, Herrmann sold the rights to one of his employees, Edward Palmer, who set up the Dyna-Cam Engine Corp. along with son Dennis.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Edward's son Dennis and daughter Pat then helped get the engine installed in a Piper Arrow airplane.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The engine was flown for about 700 hours from 1987 through 1991.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Their longest-life engine ran for nearly 4000 hours before overhaul.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] About 40 prototype engines were built by the Herrmann Group and another 25 built by the Dyna-Cam Group since they acquired the engine and opened their shop.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] A new patent was granted to Dennis Palmer and Edward Palmer, first in 1985 and then several more around 2000 to Dennis Palmer.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] In 2003 the assets of the Dyna-Cam Engine Corporation were acquired by Aero-Marine Corporation, who changed their name to Axial Vector Engine Corporation.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Axial Vector then totally re-designed the cam engine.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Axial Vector's new engine, like many of the others on this list, suffers from the "put in everything" problem, including piezoelectric valves and ignition, ceramic cylinder liners with no piston rings, and a variety of other advanced features.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It has little similarity to the original Herrmann and Dyna-Cam engines, since the Dyna-Cam engine used conventional valves, piston rings, accessories, had no unproven ceramic materials and actually flew in an aircraft and also powered a 20-foot (6.1 m) "Eliminator" ski boat for over four years.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] United Kingdom company Covaxe Limited (known as FairDiesel Limited up until 2017) is designing two-stroke Diesel opposed piston barrel engines that use non-sinusoidal cams, for industrial applications and aviation use.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Their engine designs range from a 2-cylinder, 80 mm bore to 32-cylinder, 160 mm bore.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] New Zealand company Duke Engines started in 1993 has created several different engines and installed one in a car in 1999.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The engine runs a 5-cylinder, 3 litre, 4-stroke internal combustion engine platform with its unique axial arrangement, which is in its third generation.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Due to a valveless design, Duke engine loses less energy between the power strokes.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] Current prototypes of Duke's engines claim to match characteristics of conventional internal combustion engines but with fewer parts and 30% lighter.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] This goes in the direction of developing a more efficient engine.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] During development the Duke has been tested at MAHLE Powertrain in the United Kingdom and in the United States; test results show that it has multi-fuel capabilities.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The Duke engine's benefits of lightness and compactness should render this design ideal for motorcycles engines; and these benefits might make the powerplant suitable for light aircraft as well.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] (There is little data on whether the Duke engine is smooth; the mainshaft has a large counterweight attached).
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The Cylindrical Energy Module (CEM) is a sine-wave swashplate engine that can also be used as a standalone pump, powered by an external source.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The rotating swashplate rotor assembly is moved back and forth with the help of piston drive pins, which follow a stationary sinusoidal cam track that encircles the rotor assembly.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] The CEM was designed by American inventor Eddie Paul, originally for use on fire pumps.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It was later adapted for use in automobiles, and was planned to be used in the unrealised Duesenberg Torpedo Coupe project in 2005.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] As the powerplant for the Coupe, the CEM would rotate on an axis, sucking in fuel and providing self lubrication and was capable of running on either petrol or diesel.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] It would also allegedly create only 1/6th of the heat of a conventional engine, meaning air cooling would be sufficient.
[src:engine-configuration/axial-engine] A United States company Devize Motors is currently developing a new engine utilizing opposed pistons.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] The **engine configuration** describes the fundamental operating principles by which internal combustion engines are categorized.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Piston engines are often categorized by their cylinder layout, valves and camshafts.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Wankel engines are often categorized by the number of rotors present.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Gas turbine engines are often categorized into turbojets, turbofans, turboprops and turboshafts.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] If a motor/engine is mounted in-line with the frame/chassis and in-line with the direction of travel of the vehicle it is a longitudinal motor.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] When the motor/engine is across the frame/chassis it is called a tranverse motor.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Cylinder arrangement is not in the description of how the motor/engine is oriented.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Therefore, a V4 motor/engine can be a transverse or an in-line.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Where the cylinders are arranged in two or more lines (such as in V engines or flat engines), each line of cylinders is referred to as a 'cylinder bank'.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] The angle between cylinder banks is called the 'bank angle'.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Engines with multiple banks are shorter than straight engines of the same size, and will often have better engine balance characteristics, resulting in reduced engine vibration and potentially higher maximum engine speeds.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Most engines with four or less cylinders use a straight engine layout, and most engines with eight cylinders or more use a V engine layout.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] However, there are various exceptions to this, such as the straight-eight engines used by various luxury cars from 1919-1954, V4 engines used by some marine outboard motors, V-twin and flat-twin engines used by motorcycles and flat-four engines used by various cars.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Straight engines (also known as "inline engines") have all cylinders aligned in one row along the crankshaft with no offset.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] When a straight engine is mounted at an angle, it is sometimes called a "slant engine".
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] V engines (also known as "Vee engines") have the cylinders aligned in two separate planes or 'banks', so that they appear to be in a "V" when viewed along the axis of the crankshaft.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] VR5 and VR6 engines are very compact and light, having a narrow V angle which allows a single cylinder block and cylinder head.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] These engines use a single cylinder head so are technically a straight engine with the name "VR" coming from the combination of German words “Verkürzt” and “Reihenmotor” meaning “shortened inline engine”.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Flat engines (also known as "horizontally-opposed" engines) have the cylinders arranged in two banks on either side of a single crankshaft.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Boxer engines are a subtype of flat engines where opposing pistons move in and out in tandem.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] W engines have the cylinders in a configuration in which the cylinder banks resemble the letter W, in the same way those of a V engine resemble the letter V.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] W engines using twin "VR" engine banks are technically a V engine.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] These engine banks use a single cylinder head so are technically a straight bank with the name "VR" coming from the combination of German words “Verkürzt” and “Reihenmotor” meaning “shortened inline engine”.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Radial engines have cylinders mounted radially around a central crankcase.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Rotary engines have a similar configuration, except that the crankshaft is fixed and the cylinders rotate around it.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] (This is different from the Wankel engine configuration described below.) Radial and rotary engine designs were widely used in early aircraft engines.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] U engines consist of two separate straight engines (complete with separate crankshafts) joined by gears or chains.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Most U engines have four cylinders (i.e. two straight-two engines combined), such as square four engines and tandem twin engines.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Similar to U engines, H engines consist of two separate flat engines joined by gears or chains.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] H engines have been produced with between 4 and 24 cylinders.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] An opposed-piston engine is similar to a flat engine in that pairs of pistons are co-axial but rather than sharing a crankshaft, instead share a single combustion chamber per pair of pistons.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] The crankshaft configuration varies amongst opposed-engine designs.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] One layout has a flat/boxer engine at its center and adds an additional opposed-piston to each end so there are two pistons per cylinder on each side.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] An X engine is essentially two V engines joined by a common crankshaft.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] A majority of these were existing V-12 engines converted into an X-24 configuration.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] The Swashplate engine with the K-Cycle engine is where pairs of pistons are in an opposed configuration sharing a cylinder and combustion chamber.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] A Delta engine has three (or its multiple) cylinders having opposing pistons, aligned in three separate planes or 'banks', so that they appear to be in a Δ when viewed along the axis of the main-shaft.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] An example of this type of layout is the Napier Deltic.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Wankel engines (sometimes called 'rotary engines') can be classified based on the number of rotors present.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Most production Wankel engines have two rotors, however engines with one, three and four rotors have also been produced.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Wankel engines can also be classified based on whether they are naturally aspirated or turbocharged.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Most Wankel engines are fueled by petrol, however prototype engines running on diesel and hydrogen have been trialed.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] The primary advantage of Wankel engines is the high power-to-weight ratio, as the rotational movement eliminates the need for heavy reciprocating parts like pistons and connecting rods.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Mazda is most famous for using the Wankel engine in production, featuring it on the RX-7, RX-8, and other models.
[src:engine-configuration/engine-configuration] Mazda stopped using the Wankel engine in 2012 due to various issues such as the apex seal, although they brought back the Wankel engine in 2023 with the MX-30 as a range extender for the electric battery.
